Computing MATTERS (http://www.computingmatters.org) has accomplished its ends under the CI-TEAM program and each of its parts, that is:

&bull;CyberInfrastructure: Shodor created materials for the web that touch on all aspects of CI in both content (computational science) and delivery (interactive web modles and the lesson plans to support them);

&bull;Training: CM reached hundreds of faculty and teachers and thousands of students with dynamic, visual, and interactive training that spanned a few hours to an entire school year. We used the train the trainer model to help other communities be able to offer similar programs to their own students;

&bull;Education: by expanding the computational thinking resources, especially by aligning the INTERACTIVATE and MASTER tools from Shodor to national and state standards, CM helped move successful other-than-schooltime resources into the classroom. Shodor used internships and apprenticeships focused on computatioanl thinking to complete a full re-write of INTERACTIVATE to javascript which now provides nearly 4 million page views per month of dynamic, visual, and interactive math and science activities;

&bull;Advancement: CM attracted a substantial number of young women and underrepresented minorities into the science through the enabling power of computational models;

&bull;Mentoring: Applying the train the trainer model at several levels, Shodor exposed many students in its apprenticeship and internship program to the sense of fulfillment by giving them the chance to teach what they had recently learned and mastered to others. Shodor used Computing MATTERS to mentor community leaders and teachers in schools to help them establish programs and seek and secure the funding for those projects. Two counties in partnership with CM/Shodor were able to obtain 21st Century Community Learning Center grants to expand the pilot workshops we conducted under CM to hundreds of students with their new funding.

